Captain Syrezeaju 06-Mar-20 09:23 PM
There had been no underestimation. It was just that every so often, you had to let the ice melt. There had been numerous twists and turns throughout Khassid’s life. Joining Starfleet to begin with had been one and then there were numerous along the way; from Nela to the Silescu to this. There was nothing positive about this situation, though, no ‘glimpse of light over the horizon’ or whatever the counsellors used to say. There was no single shred of positivity this time. It was unbridled guilt, and shame, and a surprisingly well-concealed anger. She could not let the anger show – untamed it would have surged through her core, that feral and unevolved Cardassian part of her clambering up to take over. She would not subject anyone to that again, and so instead, she had to shift to other emotion. Wallowing in sadness was not an option either. Khassid had learned that a long time ago in those early hours of the morning when sleep was impossible and the pain set in, lilting sound from that tiny engraved music box playing on repeat. Sadness could consume a person just like fear, and she had vowed to never drop down to that level lest it was the end of her. There would be moments to mourn in silence, there was always time to process and move on – but if you let that concept rule your life, let that mourning become a daily task and the ache wash over you like the tide, then you would become enraptured with it. There would be no way back.
It was with this line of thought that the Commodore straightened her back once more, gaze snapping upwards to meet Carlisle’s once again. Resolve was what was required, a determination to fix things and set this all right. There was no altering the past, as unfortunate as that was; and so it was foolish to go over the what ifs or what musts. That guilt and pain would remain there, hidden deep down – but it would not consume her. For the sake of herself, of the two doctors who had done so much, for this crew and for anyone else that Denn may harm in the future if not stopped; she would not give in. Declawing herself from the back of the chair she stepped around it – forcing herself to limp, not shuffle – and took the seat opposite the doctor. Her hands met that of the doctor’s outstretched own; cold meeting the warmth she seemed to radiate. How was it that the woman emitted such an atmosphere despite such trying times, despite the gravity of what Khassid had just told her? Carlisle was like a beacon, a truly exemplary medical officer; an individual of such gravitas and care. Perhaps both her and Clark were right – stardust, which had formed a sun. The words of the doctor were met with an appreciative smile, somehow. Those icy eyes blinked and flickered to that stalwart and steely gaze, the tone forcing itself to settle. Fight like she does, Khassid told herself. Look at her. What she can do, despite all of the hardship that surrounds her. She is a beacon. Fight like her. Fight. Live. I know that you can.
It was a moment before she spoke again, and when she did, the ice had frozen over once more; any sign of splintering repaired. “My fears are not for my own safety, Doctor Carlisle, only regret at what has transpired in the past. I am well aware that this cannot be altered, though. All I can do is move on. I do not fear for myself… But I do fear for anyone else who may have ended up crossing the path of Dennzen Zoyill. If they have fallen prey to him such as I did – or if anyone else does in future – then they may be faced with a similar fate to myself and my child. No one deserves to walk that path. If this is true, and I am certain that it has to be, despite how ludicrous all of it sounds; then they may be in as much danger as I.”
Commander Blanche Carlisle 07-Mar-20 10:32 AM

She offered a nod as the Cardassian broke contact, expression still solemn but much less troubled than it had been moments before. It seemed as though she had correctly mapped Khassid's passage of thought, and thus, would have to adapt to such grimness. If this were the only means to find a cure, then she'd damn well pursue it. For a moment, blue eyes quivered over Khassid's form, wrought with what she sensed to be extreme discomfort. Before Khassid could elaborate further, the door had chimed, causing Blanche to straighten up in alertness. "Come in," she called, voice masterfully void of the slight irritation she felt at such a disturbance. Any more bad news, and she might just have to stop answering the damned thing.

To: Commander Blanche Carlisle, CMO, Lt. JG. Amy Olson, ACMO
>
Live long and prosper.
>
I wish to apologize for the inconvenience earlier, and I believe I should explain why I at least appeared to walk into sickbay with a rock and demand it be scanned, lest you start to become concerned for my sanity. If I had been carrying a rock, that would have been most illogical.
>
To begin with, it was not a rock. It was mineral-based highly motile life-form that visually mimicked a rock, with an unknown place of origin, which was released for unclear reasons and without approval by a Science ensign into the Jefferies Tubes. Jefferies tubes are not a closed environment, therefore one area of immediate concern when seeing an exotic organism (or, for that matter, a group) in that environment is the potential spread of exotic pathogens. (The area has since been decontaminated, reports have been filed, and so on.) In an effort to determine whether this presented an immediate risk, I therefore brought the specimen to Sickbay for scanning, which thankfully turned up negative for any exotic pathogens. My first thought was that a medical tricorder would be necessary, and it was a spur-of-the-moment decision.
>
I must once again stress that it was not a rock, that I am perfectly fine, and that I once again apologize for the inconvenience. Should something like this occur again, I will be certain to go to the veterinary clinic on deck five.
>
Sincerely, Lt. Cmdr. T'Svai
>
P.S. I am aware in most human languages, and indeed many non-human ones, frequent repetition of a phrase is often taken as disingenuous, as is unasked for clarification. The Vulcan language lacks such idiosyncrasies. It was truly not a rock.

Aero-Prison 27-Jan-21 01:23 AM

I know that our species is more social than most and we have a complex society." On one hand she was glad that she wasnt the only one but on the other she knew that she was going to get asked the one question that she really didn't want to answer. Was she married yet. And the answer to that was no, she hadn't found a mate and she was pretty sure that she wasn't going to. Commander Blanche Carlisle 27-Jan-21 01:41 AM

"She's in this department, and couldn't be lovelier. Very social, which is why I was surprised she hadn't beat me to meetin' you. She knew that when she first went to earth she had had a hard time finding he let place. She stood and shook the doctor's hand again before smiling softly. "I appreciate your time and help, miss. I'll be sure to check in once things get settled." Commander Blanche Carlisle 27-Jan-21 07:24 PM
Upon the comm, Blanche paled. Whatever it was she was tending to upon her terminal was quickly forgotten; Kennox was onboard. Better yet, he was in the brig, and in urgent need of medical attention. After a moment's complete and utter bewilderment, Blanche hurried out into sickbay.
Commander Blanche Carlisle 28-Jan-21 06:13 PM
Compiling Kennox's log had occupied the remainder of Blanche's shift. It was with a certain level-headedness that she was able to get stuck into it, confidence in the capability of her staff suitably bolstered. Still, there was the nagging . . emptiness she felt regarding the entire ordeal — the news of Kennox's presence alone was enough to process. Dealt out with the implications of his being in the brig alongside the brutal attack on his psyche? There was no use in Blanche attempting to deny the fact she felt overwhelmed. Perhaps even that was an understatement. She felt as though she'd been hit by a freight train, and was therefore all the more inclined to get out of the office; being left in solitude to ponder the hypothetical certainly wasn't doing the woman any favors. Finalising the report, Blanche got up and headed out into the hallway. (edited)
